Here is an example implementation of Negamax algorithm in C#:

```
public static int Negamax(GameState state, int depth, int alpha, int beta, int color)
{
    if (depth == 0 || state.IsTerminal)
    {
        return color * state.Evaluate();
    }

    int bestValue = int.MinValue;
    foreach (var childState in state.GetPossibleMoves())
    {
        int value = -Negamax(childState, depth - 1, -beta, -alpha, -color);
        bestValue = Math.Max(bestValue, value);
        alpha = Math.Max(alpha, value);
        if (alpha >= beta)
        {
            break;
        }
    }
    return bestValue;
}
```

Here, `GameState` is a class that represents the current state of the game. `depth` is the maximum depth of the game tree that the algorithm will explore, `alpha` and `beta` are the bounds on the score that the algorithm will consider, and `color` is the color of the current player (1 for the first player, -1 for the second player).

The algorithm recursively explores all the possible moves from the current state up to the specified depth. For each child state, it computes the negamax value by recursively calling the negamax function with the opposite color and negating the result. It keeps track of the best value seen so far and updates the `alpha` and `beta` bounds accordingly. Finally, it returns the best value seen.

